# 🏗️ Blueprint: Isolated Cybersecurity Detection Lab (SIEM Sandbox)

This guide outlines how to architect, deploy, and utilize a fully isolated Security Operations Center (SOC) simulation environment on a virtualized host. It leverages **Wazuh** as the SIEM/XDR brain, **Microsoft Sysmon** for enhanced endpoint logging, and **Kali Linux** as the offensive simulation platform.

---

## 🌐 1. Network Topology & Isolation

To safely run security tools and simulate attacks, this entire environment must be completely segmented from your primary production network (`Cerberus`). This prevents scanning traffic or exploit payloads from interacting with stable production infrastructure.

### Network Layout

```
                          [ Physical Host (Proxmox / R710) ]
                                          |
                      =========================================
                      | Virtual Bridge: vmbr1 (Isolated LAN)  |
                      =========================================
                                          |
         -----------------------------------------------------------------
         |                                |                              |
[ Attacker Node ]                [ Defensive SIEM ]             [ Target Endpoint ]
   Kali Linux                      Wazuh Manager                    Windows 11
(192.168.99.10)                   (192.168.99.5)                  (192.168.99.20)

```

### Proxmox Network Configuration

1. Navigate to your Proxmox Node -> **System** -> **Network**.
2. Click **Create** -> **Linux Bridge**.
3. Name it `vmbr1` (or your next available sequential bridge designation).
4. Leave the **IPv4/CIDR** and **Bridge ports** entirely blank. This creates an isolated virtual switch with no physical interface attachment and no default routing to your main home network.

